.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "gem", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 1. ActiveInteraction
  :markdown

    One solution we really like is
    [ActiveInteraction](https://github.com/AaronLasseigne/active_interaction).
    It is very stable, has wonderful documentation, and gives you a clean way
    to build service objects with support for things like composed
    interactions and even ActiveModel validations.

    Add the gem to your `Gemfile` and run `bundle install`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Gemfile
      gem "active_interaction", "~> 5.3"

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "base", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 2. A Base Interaction
  :markdown

    Create a base `ApplicationInteraction` class that all of your service
    objects can inherit from. This gives you a single place to add shared
    behavior later:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # app/interactions/application_interaction.rb
      class ApplicationInteraction < ActiveInteraction::Base
        # Your interactions will inherit from this class!
      end

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "write", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 3. Writing an Interaction
  :markdown

    Each interaction declares its inputs with typed filters, runs validations,
    and implements an `execute` method. Here is a small example:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # app/interactions/users/sign_up.rb
      module Users
        class SignUp < ApplicationInteraction
          string :email
          string :name

          validates :email, presence: true

          def execute
            User.create!(email: email, name: name)
          end
        end
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Call it with `.run` (which returns an outcome you can check) or `.run!`
    (which raises on failure):

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      outcome = Users::SignUp.run(email: "ada@example.com", name: "Ada")

      if outcome.valid?
        user = outcome.result
      else
        # outcome.errors holds the validation messages
      end

= doc_note(css: "mt-8", modifier: :tip, title: "Pro Tip") do
  :markdown
    Because interactions support **composed** interactions, you can call one
    service from another with `compose`, building larger workflows out of
    small, well-tested pieces.

